{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"063627e9-75d4-4f3d-b1f4-7ff7697f2ab1","content":"It looks like the project doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required; tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWant me to scaffold the project with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ba88650-5c0b-478f-99a8-8729d341034a","outputTokens":487,"requestId":"5032:2B6299:DCAB26:FCE05C:69F2ABC9"},"id":"3aeb59ee-1cb6-4030-bc84-bb5144a6cadb","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:09:37.959Z","parentId":"d1871e3c-ef40-4f8b-b002-5d44990f9ace"}
